{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568639"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:19:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:19:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21248"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21248","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21248"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.57,0.13,0.05,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14121"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105332"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14121"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21248"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87759"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"3650"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"34172"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38113"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43744"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45002"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105332"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the General Practice with a five-day history of a mild fever, cough, and difficulty breathing. He returned from Saudi Arabia 10 days ago where he visited a camel farm, attended a crowded religious festival, went hiking and indulged in food at the local street market.  He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes, gastroesophageal reflux disease, and hypertension. His regular medications include metformin, perindopril, amlodipine and esomeprazole. His immunisations are all up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals bilateral crackles in the lower zones.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following advice should have been given to prevent transmission for the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Use DEET 20% insect repellent","Avoid consumption of unpasteurised camel milk","Avoid swimming in freshwater lakes","Use filtered water for brushing teeth","Daily Atovaquone-proguanil"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms consistent with Middle East Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus (MERS-CoV) infection, including fever, cough, and shortness of breath. His recent travel to Saudi Arabia (an endemic area) and specific exposure to camels are significant risk factors. Transmission is typically from animals to people, though there are limited cases between person-to-person.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAvoid consumption of unpasteurised camel milk\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate advice for preventing MERS-CoV transmission. Current scientific evidence indicates that dromedary camels are a major reservoir host for MERS-CoV and an important animal source of MERS infection in humans. Strains of MERS-CoV identical to human strains have been isolated from dromedaries in several countries, including Saudi Arabia, Qatar, Oman, and Egypt. The patient\u0027s history of visiting a camel farm represents a significant exposure risk. To prevent further cases, people should avoid contact with camels, consumption of raw camel milk or camel products, and handling camel waste. Eating well-cooked camel meat or pasturised camel milk is considered low risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUse DEET 20% insect repellent\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate advice for preventing MERS-CoV transmission. Unlike some other viral infections such as dengue fever, Zika virus, or malaria, coronaviruses are not transmitted by mosquitoes or other insect vectors. MERS-CoV primarily spreads through direct or indirect contact with infected dromedary camels or through close contact with infected individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAvoid swimming in freshwater lakes\u003C/strong\u003E is not relevant advice for preventing MERS-CoV. This would be more appropriate for preventing diseases such as schistosomiasis or leptospirosis, which can be contracted through exposure to contaminated freshwater. MERS-CoV is not known to be transmitted through water sources.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUse filtered water for brushing teeth\u003C/strong\u003E is not relevant for MERS-CoV prevention. This advice would be more appropriate for preventing waterborne diseases such as traveller\u0027s diarrhoea, hepatitis A, or typhoid fever in regions with unsafe drinking water. MERS-CoV is a respiratory virus and is not transmitted through contaminated water.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDaily Atovaquone-proguanil\u003C/strong\u003E is an antimalarial medication used for prophylaxis against malaria. This would be appropriate advice for preventing malaria in endemic regions, but it has no role in preventing MERS-CoV infection, which is caused by a coronavirus and not by the Plasmodium parasite that causes malaria.  It may also present with fever but less likely with cough and dyspnoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs there is no vaccine currently, patients should be warned about how to protect themselves from MERS-CoV as fatality rate is up to 36%.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["MERS-CoV transmission to humans primarily occurs through contact with infected dromedary camels, which are the major reservoir host.","Avoiding consumption of raw camel milk and close contact with camels is key to preventing MERS-CoV transmission.","MERS-CoV is not transmitted by insect vectors, water sources, or sexual contact, requiring specific preventive measures."],"references":["Australian Government Department of Health and Aged Care. Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS) [Internet]. Australian Government Department of Health and Aged Care. 2022. Available from: https://www.health.gov.au/diseases/middle-east-respiratory-syndrome-mers","WHO. Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) [Internet]. Who.int. World Health Organization: WHO; 2022. Available from: https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/middle-east-respiratory-syndrome-coronavirus-(mers-cov)"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87759"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21248"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87759"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-08T16:58:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-10T14:46:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14121"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105332"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id"